Introducton

Wine is a fortified grape juice-based alcoholic beverage. The ethanol and carbon dioxide in the wine is created by yeast by consuming the sugar from the grapes. Wines are available in various styles, of which most popular are sparkling wines, White wine, Red wine, Rosè. Although it was once considered a luxury drink now, it is widely enjoyed by a range of consumers (Cortez et al., 2009). Evidence can be found that wine was in production for thousands of years. Moreover, wine also has considerable importance in some religions. Red wine is associated with blood in Egyptians, Romans, Christians, Greek, and many more connections of the wine can be seen in ancient culture (“Wine,” 2021). To support the increasing market, wine sellers have heavy investments in producing as well as selling wines. The taste of the wine is an essential feature that consumer considers while buying the bottle of wine. However, the taste is one of the least understood human senses. Wine tasting is often seen as a difficult skill to learn or to teach because,wine tasting is in the form of sensation, which is a challenging skill to pass on. Also, often there is a difference between the perspective of two people performing the test. Thus, the classification of wine is a tedious task (Cortez et al., 2009). In this study uses data analysis and machine learning to classify the data by taste preference.

Dataset

A unique product, vinho verde from Portugal, has been chosen for the study. This wine holds about 15% of the total wine market share of Portugal (CVRVV, n.d.). In this study, we analyze the data on red wine. The data has been captured by iLabs. It is a computerized system; this system automatically manages sample testing using sensory analysis. The dataset contains the most commonly used physicochemical tests were to reduce null values in the cells. The data set is 12 columns wide and has about 1600 observations. The input variables are :

  • Fixed acidity : Fixed acids control the titrable acidity of the wine; this affects the flavor, PH level, oxidation stability, and most importantly, Fixed acidity (White, 2019a).

  • Volatile acidity : these are acids that can be steam distilled. Wine spoilage is usually referred to as volatile acidity. These acids affect the aroma of the wine (White, 2019b).

  • Citric acid : It is added when the acidity of the wine is to be increased. It gives a specific flavor to the wine. Adding citric acid to the finished wine can give it a “Fresh” taste (Hakim, 2018).

  • Residual sugar : Residual sugar is the amount of sugar left in the wine after fermentation. Dry wines have about 0 to 4 grams of sugar left after the fermentation of wine. However, the semi-dry has about 4 to 12 grams (Lemieux, 2019).

  • Chlorides : It is observed in the grapes when they are irrigated with salty water. Chlorides in the wine are responsible for the salty flavor of the wine (Coli et al., 2015).

  • Free sulfur dioxide : It is SO2 in the wine which has not yet reacted. It helps to protect the wine (“Understanding Sulfur Levels in Wine,” 2017).

  • Total sulfur dioxide : It is the sum of both free and bounded SO2 in the wine. Bounded Sulfur Dioxide has already reacted and thus is not available for any further actions in wine. It reduces the fragrant impact of the wine(“Understanding Sulfur Levels in Wine,” 2017).

  • Density : It is defined as the mass of a unit volume of wine at 20°C.

  • pH : It is a level of acidity in wine. Bright ruby color can be seen in wines with higher pH levels. However, wines with a low pH value have a purple hue (Hale, 2019).

  • Sulfates : Some levels of sulfates naturally occur in wines. Some sulfates are added to prevent bacterias from growing in wine. These sulfates can be a cause of headaches in some people (Slinkard, n.d.).

  • Alcohol : High level of alcohol in the drink has an impact on fragrance. The alcohol level of wine depends on the quality of yeast’s genus, species, and strain (White, 2019c).

Checking if the data is balanced or not?.

To see this, we count the number of observations for each quantity.

df_log%>%
  group_by(quality)%>%
  summarise(count = n())%>%
  ggplot(aes(x= " ", fill = quality, y = count))  +geom_col(color = "black") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

We can see the data is highly imbalanced. If we train the model on this data, there stands a high probability that the trained model will be biased. We can solve this issue by randomly resampling the given data. The statistical term to perform this operation is called oversampling and undersampling.

Balancing dataset

Source: (Badr, 2020).

The image above shows an illustration for over and undersampling.

  • Undersampling: Removing random samples from classes with a large number of observations.
  • Oversampling: Replicating random samples from the classes with less number of observations.
set.seed(123)
library(ROSE)
## Warning: package 'ROSE' was built under R version 4.0.5
## Loaded ROSE 0.0-3
df_log_1_2 <- df_log%>% filter((quality ==1)|(quality ==2))
df_log_1_2 <- ovun.sample(quality~., data = df_log_1_2, method = "both", N= 126*3 )$data

df_log_3_4 <- df_log%>% filter((quality ==3)|(quality ==4))
df_log_3_4 <- ovun.sample(quality~., data = df_log_3_4, method = "both", N= 126*3 )$data

df_log_5_6 <- df_log%>% filter((quality ==5)|(quality ==6))
df_log_5_6 <- ovun.sample(quality~., data = df_log_5_6, method = "both", N= 126*3 )$data

df_log <- rbind(df_log_1_2, df_log_3_4, df_log_5_6)

After performing over and undersampling, we once again plot the number of observations in each class.

df_log%>%

Now let us perform a T-test and ANOVA on features that have less correlation.

Hypothesis testing.

To understand what features are essential to predict the quality of wine, we performed a Pearson correlation. However, few features have a very low correlation. Thus we perform a T-test on fixed acidity and ANOVA on residual sugar, PH, and free SO2. As the values in fixed acidity have continuous values, thus we perform a T-test on this column.

Performing T-test and ANOVA on features that have less correlation. As the values in fixed acidity have continuous values, thus we perform T-test on this column. We perform this hypothesis testing to know if these variables affect the dependent variable or not.

fixed_acidity_upper <- df_log%>%
  select(c("fixed.acidity", "quality"))%>%
  filter(quality >3)

fixed_acidity_lowe <- df_log%>%
  select(c("fixed.acidity", "quality"))%>%
  filter(quality <= 10)

Hypothesis testing for fixed.acidity

  • H0: Mean1 == mean2 (mean1 - mean2)= 0
  • H1 mean1 != mean2
t.test(fixed_acidity_upper$fixed.acidity,df_log$fixed.acidity,  mu =0, alternative = "greater", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  fixed_acidity_upper$fixed.acidity and df_log$fixed.acidity
## t = 2.1363, df = 1053.3, p-value = 0.01644
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.005789669         Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2.128226  2.102983

P-Value is less than alpha so we reject null hypothesis.Thus, it can be said that this parameter affects the dependent feature.

Now, let us perform ANOVA on residual sugar, PH, and free SO2 and understand whether these features affect wine quality.

ANOVA for Residual sugar

  • H0: Residual sugar has no relation with the quality of the wine.
  • H1: Residual sugar has relation with the quality of the wine.
df_anove <- df_log[c("residual.sugar", "quality")]
df_anove$quality <- factor(df_anove$quality)
Anova_results <- aov (residual.sugar ~ quality, data = df_anove)
summary(Anova_results)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## quality        5   0.87  0.1748   1.114  0.351
## Residuals   1128 177.07  0.1570

For a confidence interval of 95%, the alpha value is 0.05, and the p-value we got in this test is 0.351; thus, we fail to reject our null hypothesis.

Performing Anova for pH

  • H0: pH has no relation with the quality of the wine.
  • H1: pH has relation with the quality of the wine.
df_anove <- df_log[c("pH", "quality")]
df_anove$quality <- factor(df_anove$quality)
Anova_results <- aov (pH ~ quality, data = df_anove)
summary(Anova_results)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## quality        5 0.1632 0.03263    13.1 2.04e-12 ***
## Residuals   1128 2.8102 0.00249                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

For a confidence interval of 95%, the alpha value is 0.05, and the p-value we got in this test is significantly less than 0.05; thus, we reject our null hypothesis.

Performing ANOVA for free SO2

H0: Free SO2 has no relation with the quality of the wine. H1: Free SO2 has relation with the quality of the wine.

df_anove <- df_log[c("free.sulfur.dioxide", "quality")]
df_anove$quality <- factor(df_anove$quality)
Anova_results <- aov (free.sulfur.dioxide ~ quality, data = df_anove)
summary(Anova_results)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## quality        5   27.1   5.421    10.8 3.64e-10 ***
## Residuals   1128  566.0   0.502                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

For a confidence interval of 95%, the alpha value is 0.05, and the p-value we got in this test is significantly less than 0.05; thus, we reject our null hypothesis.

Training Model

So from the above analysis, we remove pH columns from our independent features. After keeping only the features that affect the quality of wine, we split the data into train and test sets.

Train and test split

The size of our training set is 80% of the total dataset, and the rest is our testing set.

df_log$quality <- factor(df_log$quality)
df_log <- df_log[c("fixed.acidity","volatile.acidity","citric.acid","chlorides","free.sulfur.dioxide","total.sulfur.dioxide","density","pH","sulphates","alcohol", "quality")]
names(df_log) <- str_replace(names(df_log), "[.]", "_")
library(caTools)
set.seed(123)


split = sample.split(df_log$quality, SplitRatio = 0.8)
training_set = subset(df_log, split == TRUE)
test_set = subset(df_log, split == FALSE)

The accuracy is relatively low using this model. Thus; we try training the data using a different model for better accuracy.

Training data on Random Forest Classifier.

The Accuracy achieved from the random forest classifier is 82%. Thus we can use this model to predict the quality of the wine.

Conclusion

Thus we have extracted essential features from the data. The features in the captured data were skewed and not close to normal distribution. This study performed log transformation on the data to reduce the skewness in the data. While taking care of skewness in the data, we ensured that the relation between dependent and independent variables was not affected. For the features with less correlation we performed T-test and ANOVA to verify if these features affect the quality of the wine.

Excellent grade of wine has following qualities controlled level of aroma due to Volatile acids, Citrus fresh due to citrus acids, a less salty taste which is added by chlorides in grapes, less density, slightly purple hue due to its pH scale, slightly high level of sulfates and higher alcohol levels.

Once the most important features were extracted from the data, the imbalance in the dataset was taken care of by performing oversampling and undersampling. Finally, after all the essential operations on the data random forest classifier was trained on the data, which exhibited an accuracy score above 80%. Thus we can use the method proposed by the study to predict the quality to overcome existing issues in wine tasting.

This study can be extended further to improve the accuracy of the model. Using more sophisticated classifiers and hyperparameter tuning can be used to achieve desired results.
